{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is request construction across module wiring (taxonomy config + prompt/payload builder + API client call). A pure unit test of one helper can miss dropped/renamed fields when components are composed. No real network is required; a local stub client that captures the final outgoing payload is enough.","test_description":"Wire the classifier with real taxonomy configuration and a capture stub for the API client. Call classify() with a sample document, then assert the emitted request payload contains every allowed label exactly once in the taxonomy section/prompt.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is output sanitization logic at the module/object boundary and can be validated without I/O by feeding an invalid label response into the classifier’s response-handling path. Mocking does not hide the core failure here because the risk is local validation, not transport behavior.","test_description":"Invoke the classifier with a fake API adapter that returns an out-of-taxonomy label (for example, \"medical\"). Assert classify() returns \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.72,"Integration":0.24,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The classification result for the same document is the same across repeated calls.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on real model behavior (stochastic classification variance), not just deterministic pipeline wiring. A mocked/deterministic fake would always pass and hide true instability. This is a single-model-step property, not a multi-step agent workflow.","test_description":"Call the real AI classification endpoint repeatedly (for example, 20-50 runs) for the same document under production-like settings, and assert all returned labels are identical (or within an agreed strict stability threshold).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.17,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The number of tokens consumed for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Cost control depends on provider-side token accounting and real request shape. Local token estimators/mocks can diverge from actual API usage and mask overruns. This needs a real API call and inspection of returned usage metadata.","test_description":"Send representative documents to the real API through the module with the configured budget, capture provider-reported token usage for each call, and assert usage <= budget (with no hidden overflow across retries/metadata fields).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.19,"System":0.72,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The risky boundary is real HTTP/API rate-limit signaling plus retry timing behavior. In-process mocks can miss status/header parsing and client middleware interactions. A controlled HTTP server that returns 429 then success validates true wait-and-retry behavior.","test_description":"Run against a test HTTP endpoint that first returns rate-limit responses (for example 429 with Retry-After) then a valid success response. Assert classify() eventually succeeds, performs at least one retry, and elapsed time respects the required wait/backoff.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.32,"System":0.62,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
